Certainly! Here's an example implementation of the Fibonacci sequence using tabulation in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int fibonacci_tabulation(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) {
        return 0;
    }

    std::vector<int> fib_table(n + 1, 0); // create a vector or array of size n+1

    fib_table[0] = 0;
    fib_table[1] = 1;

    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
        fib_table[i] = fib_table[i - 1] + fib_table[i - 2];
    }

    return fib_table[n];
}

int main() {
    int n = 10; // Example value, you can change it to any number you want
    int result = fibonacci_tabulation(n);
    std::cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << result << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this C++ implementation, we use an `std::vector` named `fib_table` to represent the table for tabulation. We initialize the vector with size `n+1` and fill it with initial values of 0.

Then, similar to the previous implementation, we use a for loop to iteratively calculate each Fibonacci number, filling in the table by summing up the previous two values.

Finally, in the `main()` function, we provide an example usage by calling `fibonacci_tabulation()` with a value of `n` (in this case, set to 10), and print the result.

You can modify the value of `n` in the `main()` function to calculate the desired Fibonacci number.

